  <h1>SpacetimeDB Architecture</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">External effects, design invariants, and where AI inference fits in a SpacetimeDB system.</p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════ SECTION 1 ═══════════════════════════════ -->

  <h2 id="invariants">Design Invariants</h2>
  <p>SpacetimeDB is built on three properties that are non-negotiable by design. Every architectural decision flows from maintaining them.</p>

  <div class="diagram-wrap">
    <svg width="100%" viewBox="0 0 680 130" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="Segoe UI, system-ui, sans-serif">
      <!-- Determinism -->
      <rect x="20" y="20" width="190" height="90" rx="8" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#2a2f45"/>
      <text x="115" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="#5b8ef7" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">DETERMINISM</text>
      <text x="115" y="70" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">Given identical inputs,</text>
      <text x="115" y="86" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">every replica produces</text>
      <text x="115" y="102" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">identical state.</text>
      <!-- Atomicity -->
      <rect x="245" y="20" width="190" height="90" rx="8" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#2a2f45"/>
      <text x="340" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="#5b8ef7" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">ATOMICITY</text>
      <text x="340" y="70" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">State transitions are</text>
      <text x="340" y="86" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">all-or-nothing. No</text>
      <text x="340" y="102" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">partial writes exist.</text>
      <!-- Subscriptions -->
      <rect x="470" y="20" width="190" height="90" rx="8" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#2a2f45"/>
      <text x="565" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="#5b8ef7" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">LIVE SUBSCRIPTIONS</text>
      <text x="565" y="70" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">Clients observe state</text>
      <text x="565" y="86" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">changes as they happen;</text>
      <text x="565" y="102" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">they do not poll.</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>The three properties SpacetimeDB is designed to preserve.</figcaption>
  </div>

  <p>
    Determinism requires that reducers — the only mechanism for mutating state — must produce the same output for the same input unconditionally. This rules out any I/O inside a reducer: no network calls, no randomness from outside, no filesystem reads.
  </p>

  <!-- ─── Reducer model ─── -->
  <h2 id="reducer-model">The Reducer Model</h2>
  <p>
    A reducer is a function that runs inside the database, reads current table state, and writes new table state. It is the unit of transactional logic. All state changes flow through reducers; there is no direct write path for clients.
  </p>

  <div class="diagram-wrap">
    <svg width="100%" viewBox="0 0 660 160" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="Segoe UI, system-ui, sans-serif">
      <!-- Client -->
      <rect x="20" y="50" width="110" height="60" rx="8" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#3dd68c" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <text x="75" y="76" text-anchor="middle" fill="#3dd68c" font-size="11" font-weight="700">CLIENT</text>
      <text x="75" y="92" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">calls reducer</text>
      <text x="75" y="106" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">with arguments</text>
      <!-- Arrow 1 -->
      <line x1="135" y1="80" x2="190" y2="80" stroke="#2a2f45" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <polygon points="190,75 200,80 190,85" fill="#2a2f45"/>
      <text x="165" y="72" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7298" font-size="10">invoke</text>
      <!-- Reducer box -->
      <rect x="205" y="30" width="250" height="100" rx="8" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#5b8ef7" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <text x="330" y="56" text-anchor="middle" fill="#5b8ef7" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">REDUCER (in DB)</text>
      <text x="330" y="76" text-anchor="middle" fill="#d4d8f0" font-size="11">reads current state</text>
      <text x="330" y="92" text-anchor="middle" fill="#d4d8f0" font-size="11">applies logic</text>
      <text x="330" y="108" text-anchor="middle" fill="#d4d8f0" font-size="11">writes new state — atomically</text>
      <!-- Arrow 2 -->
      <line x1="460" y1="80" x2="510" y2="80" stroke="#2a2f45" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <polygon points="510,75 520,80 510,85" fill="#2a2f45"/>
      <text x="487" y="72" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7298" font-size="10">emits</text>
      <!-- Tables -->
      <rect x="525" y="50" width="110" height="60" rx="8" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#7c5bf7" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <text x="580" y="76" text-anchor="middle" fill="#7c5bf7" font-size="11" font-weight="700">TABLES</text>
      <text x="580" y="92" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">updated state</text>
      <text x="580" y="106" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">pushed to subs</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>All state mutation is mediated by a reducer. Clients invoke; reducers act; subscribers observe.</figcaption>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Client correction ─── -->
  <h2 id="client-correction">Correcting the Client Model</h2>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>The model to revise:</strong> "the client sends a payload and a system applies logic to it before it is recorded."
  </div>

  <p>
    That framing implies a pipeline — payload travels to the database, something intercepts it, transforms it, then stores it. SpacetimeDB does not work this way. The reducer <em>is</em> the transformation step, and it runs entirely inside the database as an atomic unit. There is no pre-processing stage external to the reducer.
  </p>
  <p>
    The corrected model: the client sends a <strong>command</strong> — a reducer name plus arguments. The reducer is the logic that validates, transforms, and commits state. The client has no role in the logic; it only provides inputs and observes outputs via subscriptions.
  </p>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="card bad">
      <h4>Incorrect mental model</h4>
      <p>Client sends data → middleware transforms it → database stores it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card good">
      <h4>Correct mental model</h4>
      <p>Client invokes a reducer → reducer reads + transforms + writes, atomically.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr/>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════ SECTION 2 ═══════════════════════════════ -->

  <h2 id="effects-problem">The External Effects Problem</h2>

  <p>
    Your intuition is sound: if the system's logic is meant to live in the database, having a client-side process orchestrate an LLM call and then feed the result in feels architecturally incoherent — the intelligence is stranded outside the system boundary.
  </p>
  <p>
    But the tension dissolves once the right distinction is drawn. The issue is not about where logic lives. It is about the difference between <em>logic</em> and <em>effects</em>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="reframe">Logic vs. Effect</h2>

  <div class="diagram-wrap">
    <svg width="100%" viewBox="0 0 660 170" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="Segoe UI, system-ui, sans-serif">
      <!-- Logic side -->
      <rect x="20" y="20" width="290" height="130" rx="8" fill="rgba(91,142,247,0.05)" stroke="rgba(91,142,247,0.3)" stroke-dasharray="5,3"/>
      <text x="165" y="44" text-anchor="middle" fill="#5b8ef7" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">LOGIC  (lives in reducers)</text>
      <text x="165" y="70" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">Given state S and command C,</text>
      <text x="165" y="88" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">what is the next state S'?</text>
      <text x="165" y="112" text-anchor="middle" fill="#d4d8f0" font-size="11">Pure, deterministic, transactional.</text>
      <text x="165" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="#d4d8f0" font-size="11">No I/O. No side effects.</text>

      <!-- Effects side -->
      <rect x="350" y="20" width="290" height="130" rx="8" fill="rgba(247,195,91,0.05)" stroke="rgba(247,195,91,0.3)" stroke-dasharray="5,3"/>
      <text x="495" y="44" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f7c35b" font-size="11" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">EFFECTS  (live outside DB)</text>
      <text x="495" y="70" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">Producing inputs for the system:</text>
      <text x="495" y="88" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">player commands, sensor data,</text>
      <text x="495" y="106" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="11">AI decisions, external lookups.</text>
      <text x="495" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="#d4d8f0" font-size="11">Inherently non-deterministic.</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>The fundamental separation. SpacetimeDB owns the left side by design. The right side belongs to the boundary.</figcaption>
  </div>

  <p>
    An LLM inference call is an <em>effect</em> — it is the act of producing a non-deterministic input. What the system <em>does with that input</em> — validating it, integrating it into game state, triggering downstream state changes — is <em>logic</em>, and belongs in a reducer.
  </p>
  <p>
    SpacetimeDB's invariant is not "all computation lives in the database." It is "all <strong>state transitions</strong> are deterministic and atomic." These are compatible with external effects, provided the effects are positioned correctly at the system boundary.
  </p>

  <div class="callout ok">
    <strong>The reframe:</strong> The LLM is not app logic being displaced to the wrong layer. It is an input source — equivalent in kind to a player pressing a key — that happens to require an external service to produce. The database correctly handles what to do with the result.
  </div>

  <hr/>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════ SECTION 3 ═══════════════════════════════ -->

  <h2 id="pattern">The Intent &amp; Oracle Pattern</h2>

  <p>
    The canonical solution is to model the LLM call as an asynchronous, two-phase interaction. The database expresses a <strong>need</strong>; an external service fulfills it; the result re-enters through the standard reducer invocation path.
  </p>

  <div class="diagram-wrap">
    <svg width="100%" viewBox="0 0 720 280" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="Segoe UI, system-ui, sans-serif">
      <!-- Column headers -->
      <text x="90" y="22" text-anchor="middle" fill="#3dd68c" font-size="10" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">SPACETIMEDB</text>
      <text x="380" y="22" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f7c35b" font-size="10" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">AI AGENT PROCESS</text>
      <text x="620" y="22" text-anchor="middle" fill="#7c5bf7" font-size="10" font-weight="700" letter-spacing="1">LLM API</text>

      <!-- Vertical lanes -->
      <line x1="200" y1="30" x2="200" y2="270" stroke="#2a2f45" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <line x1="520" y1="30" x2="520" y2="270" stroke="#2a2f45" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>

      <!-- Step 1: reducer writes intent -->
      <rect x="20" y="44" width="160" height="40" rx="6" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#3dd68c" stroke-width="1.2"/>
      <text x="100" y="60" text-anchor="middle" fill="#3dd68c" font-size="10" font-weight="700">reducer runs</text>
      <text x="100" y="76" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">writes Intent record to table</text>

      <!-- Step 2: subscription fires -->
      <line x1="180" y1="84" x2="240" y2="110" stroke="#5b8ef7" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
      <text x="220" y="103" fill="#6b7298" font-size="10">subscription fires</text>

      <!-- Step 3: agent reads intent -->
      <rect x="250" y="114" width="170" height="40" rx="6" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#f7c35b" stroke-width="1.2"/>
      <text x="335" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f7c35b" font-size="10" font-weight="700">agent sees pending Intent</text>
      <text x="335" y="146" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">reads game state from subscription</text>

      <!-- Step 4: LLM call -->
      <line x1="420" y1="134" x2="540" y2="134" stroke="#7c5bf7" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
      <text x="480" y="127" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7298" font-size="10">HTTP request</text>
      <rect x="545" y="114" width="150" height="40" rx="6" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#7c5bf7" stroke-width="1.2"/>
      <text x="620" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="#7c5bf7" font-size="10" font-weight="700">LLM inference</text>
      <text x="620" y="146" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">non-deterministic I/O</text>

      <!-- Step 5: response -->
      <line x1="545" y1="174" x2="425" y2="174" stroke="#7c5bf7" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr3)"/>
      <text x="480" y="167" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7298" font-size="10">decision returned</text>

      <!-- Step 6: agent calls reducer -->
      <rect x="250" y="188" width="170" height="40" rx="6" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#f7c35b" stroke-width="1.2"/>
      <text x="335" y="204" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f7c35b" font-size="10" font-weight="700">agent calls reducer</text>
      <text x="335" y="220" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">fulfill_intent(id, decision)</text>

      <!-- Step 7: reducer processes result -->
      <line x1="250" y1="208" x2="180" y2="230" stroke="#5b8ef7" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr4)"/>

      <rect x="20" y="230" width="160" height="36" rx="6" fill="#1e2333" stroke="#3dd68c" stroke-width="1.2"/>
      <text x="100" y="248" text-anchor="middle" fill="#3dd68c" font-size="10" font-weight="700">reducer processes result</text>
      <text x="100" y="260" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9099c0" font-size="10">updates game state atomically</text>

      <!-- Arrowhead markers -->
      <defs>
        <marker id="arr" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
          <path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#5b8ef7"/>
        </marker>
        <marker id="arr2" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
          <path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#7c5bf7"/>
        </marker>
        <marker id="arr3" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="2" refY="3" orient="auto">
          <path d="M8,0 L8,6 L0,3 z" fill="#7c5bf7"/>
        </marker>
        <marker id="arr4" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="2" refY="3" orient="auto">
          <path d="M8,0 L8,6 L0,3 z" fill="#5b8ef7"/>
        </marker>
      </defs>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>The Intent &amp; Oracle pattern. Non-determinism is isolated to the agent process; the database sees only deterministic inputs and outputs.</figcaption>
  </div>

  <p>The pattern has four key properties:</p>
  <ul style="margin: 0 0 16px 20px; color: var(--text);">
    <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>The database expresses intent, not a request.</strong> The Intent record says "an AI decision is needed for unit X in situation Y" — it is a fact about current state, not a side effect.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>The non-deterministic call is isolated.</strong> The LLM response lives entirely in the agent process until it is explicitly fed back as a reducer argument.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>Results re-enter as standard inputs.</strong> <code>fulfill_intent</code> is a reducer like any other. The database does not know or care that the argument came from an LLM.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>Determinism is fully preserved.</strong> Every replica sees the same <code>fulfill_intent</code> call with the same arguments and produces the same state transition.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ─── Agent identity ─── -->
  <h2 id="agent-identity">The Agent as a Participant, Not a Client</h2>

  <p>
    This distinction matters for the question of where logic lives. A player client is also "outside the database" — it observes state and invokes reducers. If having the client make an LLM call felt wrong, the issue was not the network hop; it was that a player client carries the wrong identity and trust level to make authoritative game decisions.
  </p>
  <p>
    The AI agent process is not a player. It is a <strong>trusted system participant</strong> with its own identity, its own SpacetimeDB credentials, and potentially elevated reducer permissions. Its role is structurally identical to a game server process: it subscribes to state, applies external reasoning, and drives state changes via authenticated reducer calls.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Where logic lives:</strong> The rules governing what the AI <em>can</em> do, what moves are legal, and how the result integrates into game state all live in reducers. What the AI <em>decides</em> to do — the policy — is computed externally and provided as input. This is not a compromise of the design; it is the correct boundary.
  </div>

