  <!-- ─── Analogies ─── -->
  <h2 id="analogy">Broader Analogies</h2>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>The Elm Architecture</h4>
      <p>The <code>update</code> function is a pure state machine. Side effects are commands returned to the runtime, which executes them and feeds results back as messages. SpacetimeDB reducers are the <code>update</code> function. The AI agent is the runtime.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Hexagonal Architecture</h4>
      <p>The domain (SpacetimeDB) defines ports. External services (LLM, clients) are adapters. The domain never reaches out; adapters push data in through the defined interface — reducer invocations.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Event Sourcing / CQRS</h4>
      <p>The Intent table is a command queue. The AI agent is a command handler that requires external data. The result is a new command (<code>fulfill_intent</code>). The event log remains fully deterministic.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Actor Model</h4>
      <p>The AI agent is an actor. It has a mailbox (the Intent table via subscription), does local computation (LLM call), and sends a message (reducer invocation). The database is the authoritative actor that manages all shared state.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Summary ─── -->
  <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>

  <p>SpacetimeDB's invariants are not in conflict with external AI inference. The conflict only appears when logic and effects are conflated. The resolution:</p>

  <ul style="margin: 0 0 24px 20px; color: var(--text);">
    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><span class="tag db">DB</span> Reducers own all state transitions. They are the logic layer — pure, atomic, deterministic.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><span class="tag ext">Agent</span> The AI agent process owns all effects. It subscribes to state, calls the LLM, and submits results back through reducer invocations.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><span class="tag client">Client</span> Player clients are also participants. They submit commands (reducer calls) and observe state. They should not orchestrate AI logic.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout ok">
    <strong>The invariant preserved:</strong> every state transition the database makes is still deterministic and atomic. The LLM's non-determinism is fully contained at the system boundary. The database has no knowledge of, or dependency on, external services.
  </div>

